n in Gloucestershire, which may derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hortin","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Horton was born before 1217, in Southwick, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Roger Horton. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"Bef 1217–":"enne 1217–Surnud","1215–1270":"1215–1270","1217–Male":"1217–Surnud","1223–Male":"1223–Surnud","1238–1268":"1238–1268","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1247–Male":"1247–Surnud","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1190":"1190","1217":"1217","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1247":"1247","1268":"1268","1223":"1223","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","Bef 1217":"enne 1217","Southwick, Northampton, England":"Southwick, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Bef 1217–":"ennen vuotta 1217–Kuollut","1215–1270":"1215–1270","1217–Male":"1217–Kuollut","1223–Male":"1223–Kuollut","1238–1268":"1238–1268","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1247–Male":"1247–Kuollut